    {
        "content": "<p>I am now surprised that I didn't run into this in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/1a9b964b92509b9a757fd24bae6b6b9812443163/Mathlib/Topology/Algebra/Module/ModuleTopology.lean#L432-L464\">my proof that the product of the module topolgoies was the module topology</a>, but on re-examining the proof I think that I get away with this</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"c1\">-- In this proof, `M × N` always denotes the product with its *product* topology.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">...</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"c1\">-- Or equivalently, if `P` denotes `M × N` with the module topology,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">P</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">M</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">×</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">N</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">τP</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">TopologicalSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">P</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">moduleTopology</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">P</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">...</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>because although I've just learnt that apparently P would have got the product topology, I immediately overrid it with the module topology, giving me defeq <code>P</code> and <code>M × N</code> with typeclass inference putting two different topologies on them anyway.</p>",
